---
requires:
  - arbiter-core
import:
  - typescript-react-app-template
description: >-
  Arbiter web app: fetches real London billboard inventory, runs a live
  multi-round auction with Claude-backed advertiser agents, and renders a 3D
  scene plus an auditable per-agent scorecard. All money figures come from
  arbiter-core; the app only displays them.
---

***definitions***

- :OverpassQuery: is the request sent to the OpenStreetMap Overpass API.
  - It asks for advertising billboards inside the London bounding box.

- :PricingModel: turns a raw billboard's area into a deterministic, documented basePrice and bidIncrement.
  - It produces the pricing for a :BillboardSlot:.
  - It is a transparent function of the billboard, not a live market rate.

- :InventorySource: fetches real London billboards through :OverpassQuery:.
  - It normalises each into a :BillboardSlot: using :PricingModel:, and caches the first fetch.

- :BidDecision: is one agent's choice for one contested slot in one round.
  - The choice is raise, hold, or drop, plus the raise amount when raising.

- :AgentRuntime: wraps one :AdvertiserAgent: as a live bidder.
  - Given the public auction state it returns a :BidDecision: per contested slot it wants.
  - It never returns an action that exceeds the agent's remaining budget.

- :RoundEvent: is a streamed snapshot of one round.
  - It carries the round number, the standing bid per contested slot, the drop-outs so far, and remaining budgets.

- :ArenaOrchestrator: runs the auction.
  - It drives synchronized rounds and collects a :BidDecision: from each :AgentRuntime:.
  - It appends the resulting valid :Bid: and :DropOut: events to an :AuctionLog: and advances until every slot clears.
  - When the auction ends it calls :ClearingEngine: then :Referee: to produce the final results.

- :RoundStream: is the channel that pushes each :RoundEvent: to the browser as the auction runs.

- :LondonMapScene: is the React Three Fiber scene.
  - It is a London map plane with one node per :BillboardSlot:, placed by latitude and longitude.

- :BidEdge: is a short-lived visual edge drawn from a bidding agent to the slot it bid on when a :Bid: happens.

- :ClearingPulse: is the visual settling that plays when a :ClearingResult: arrives.
  - It locks each slot node to its winner's colour and final price.

- :ScorecardPanel: is the per-agent panel that displays an :AgentScorecard: exactly as arbiter-core produced it.

- :AuctionHUD: is the round ticker overlay.
  - It shows the current round, the standing bid per contested slot, and remaining budgets.

***implementation reqs***

- :InventorySource: fetches from the public OpenStreetMap Overpass API, which needs no API key.
  - The Overpass endpoint defaults to the runtime value `https://overpass-api.de/api/interpreter`, overridable by env.
  - The London bounding box is south 51.28, west -0.51, north 51.70, east 0.33.
  - The first fetch is live; its normalised result is written to the cache file `public/cache/london_inventory.json`.
  - Later runs read that cache file instead of calling Overpass again.
- :PricingModel: computes basePrice as a documented function of the billboard's estimated face area in square metres.
  - basePrice = 50 pounds plus 25 pounds per square metre of face area, rounded to the nearest whole pound.
  - When area is unknown, a default face area of 12 square metres is assumed.
  - bidIncrement = 10 percent of basePrice, rounded to the nearest whole pound, with a floor of 5 pounds.
  - This formula is presented to the user as a transparent estimate, never as a live market rate.
- :AgentRuntime: makes its bidding decisions with the Claude API, one call per agent per decision.
  - The default model is `claude-sonnet-4-6`, overridable by env; the API key is read from env `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`.
  - Each agent's prompt is private: it contains only that agent's own budget, its own per-slot valuation, and its goal.
  - One agent's valuation is never placed in another agent's prompt.
- :ArenaOrchestrator: depends on the :AgentRuntime: decision contract, not on the Claude API directly.
  - This lets tests inject a deterministic :AgentRuntime: while production wires the Claude-backed one.
- The deterministic auction maths is delegated entirely to arbiter-core, imported from `src/core/`.
  - The app never recomputes a cleared price, fair price, overpayment, surplus, or left-on-table value.
- :RoundStream: pushes :RoundEvent: updates over a WebSocket; a Server-Sent-Events channel is an acceptable fallback.
- The default auction runs with 4 advertiser agents over the London inventory.
- The 3D scene caps device pixel ratio at 2 and always fills the browser viewport.

***functional specs***

- Implement the Arbiter app entry point.
  - `index.html` loads `src/main.tsx`, which mounts the root React component into the `#root` element.
  - The root component shows an empty London stage and a control to start an auction.
  - Running `npm run dev` serves the app on Vite's dev server.

- Implement :PricingModel: as a stateless component that derives slot pricing from a billboard.
  - It exposes one operation that takes a billboard's face area in square metres.
  - It returns basePrice and bidIncrement.
  - It applies the documented pricing formula, assuming the default face area when area is missing.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - A billboard with a face area of 12 square metres yields basePrice 350 and bidIncrement 35.

- Implement :InventorySource: fetching and normalisation from :OverpassQuery:.
  - It queries the Overpass endpoint for advertising billboards within the London bounding box.
  - It normalises each returned element into a :BillboardSlot:.
    - Each :BillboardSlot: gets a stable id, a name, a latitude, a longitude, and pricing from :PricingModel:.
  - It returns the list of normalised :BillboardSlot: items.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - A fetch returns at least one normalised :BillboardSlot:.
  - Every returned slot has a latitude within 51.28 to 51.70 and a longitude within -0.51 to 0.33.

- Implement :InventorySource: caching so only the first fetch is live.
  - On the first call, after a successful live fetch, the normalised slots are written to the cache file.
  - On any later call, the slots are read from that cache file and no Overpass request is made.
  - The cached set is identical to the set returned by the first fetch.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - Calling :InventorySource: a second time returns the same set of :BillboardSlot: items as the first call.
  - The second call issues no network request.

- Implement the :AgentRuntime: decision contract and its budget enforcement.
  - :AgentRuntime: exposes one operation: given the public auction state, return a :BidDecision: per wanted slot.
  - A raise :BidDecision: whose amount would exceed the agent's remaining budget is rejected and downgraded to a drop.
    - So the runtime never emits an over-budget action.
  - The contract is satisfiable by a deterministic implementation for testing, independent of any Claude call.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - Take an :AgentRuntime: for an agent with remaining budget 120, asked to act where a valid raise would be 130.
  - It never returns a raise; it returns a drop or hold, and the rejected over-budget raise is recorded as the reason.

- Implement the Claude-backed :AgentRuntime: that produces live :BidDecision: values.
  - For each decision it makes one Claude API call with the agent's private prompt.
    - The private prompt holds the agent's budget, its per-slot valuation, and its goal.
  - It parses the model reply into a :BidDecision: per slot, then applies the budget guard from the prior spec.
  - A malformed or missing reply is treated as a hold for that slot.

- Implement the :ArenaOrchestrator: round loop that runs a full headless auction to completion.
  - Every agent is a contender for a slot until it drops out of that slot.
    - A contender that has not yet bid still counts as a contender.
    - A slot is contested while two or more contenders remain on it.
    - A slot clears when exactly one contender remains; that contender is the winner.
    - The slot is NOT settled merely because only one agent has bid so far — others may still enter.
  - Within a round the orchestrator processes agents one at a time in a fixed order.
    - It asks each agent for its :BidDecision: from the live state.
    - The live state already reflects every :Bid: and :DropOut: made earlier in the same round.
  - On a slot with no standing bid yet, a contender enters by bidding at least the slot basePrice.
  - On a slot that already has a standing bid, a non-leading contender does one of:
    - raise to at least the standing bid plus the slot bidIncrement, becoming the new leader; or
    - drop out, recording priceAtDropOut as the standing bid it declined to beat.
  - The current leader of a slot takes no action that round and stays a contender.
  - The loop advances rounds until every slot has cleared, then stops.
  - Termination is guaranteed: each round every non-leading contender either raises the price or drops out.
    - An agent that cannot afford the next raise drops out, so contenders only ever decrease.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - A headless single-slot run with two deterministic agents, where one keeps raising and the other drops once the price
    passes its limit, terminates with the slot cleared and exactly one winner.
  - In that run the losing agent appears in the :AuctionLog: with a drop-out, proving the slot was genuinely contested.
  - The resulting :AuctionLog: passes :AuctionValidator: with no violations.

- Implement :ArenaOrchestrator: final scoring once the auction ends.
  - It calls :ClearingEngine: on the completed :AuctionLog: to get a :ClearingResult: per slot.
  - It then calls :Referee: with the results, the log, and the agents to get one :AgentScorecard: per agent.
  - It returns a final bundle of the slots, the :AuctionLog:, the clearing results, and the scorecards.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - After a headless run, the final bundle has one :ClearingResult: per slot and one :AgentScorecard: per agent.
  - For every agent, the bundle's :AgentScorecard: equals :Referee: run directly on the bundle's own :AuctionLog: and
    clearing results — proving the orchestrator only relays core output and never recomputes it.

- Implement :RoundEvent: streaming through :RoundStream:.
  - As the orchestrator finishes each round it emits a :RoundEvent:.
    - The :RoundEvent: holds the round number, the standing bid per contested slot, the drop-outs so far, and budgets.
  - :RoundStream: pushes each :RoundEvent: to connected clients over a WebSocket, with a Server-Sent-Events fallback.
  - The browser receives the rounds in order.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - Running a three-round auction emits exactly three :RoundEvent: messages in round order.
  - Each message carries the standing bid for every still-contested slot.

- Implement :LondonMapScene: as a full-viewport React Three Fiber canvas.
  - The scene mounts a Canvas that fills the viewport, with a London map plane and ambient plus directional lighting.
  - The canvas caps device pixel ratio at 2 and resizes to stay full-viewport when the window changes size.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - The Canvas mounts with at least one ambient and one directional light present and fills the viewport.
  - After a window resize it keeps a device pixel ratio no greater than 2.

- Implement :BillboardSlot: nodes inside :LondonMapScene:.
  - Each :BillboardSlot: becomes one node positioned on the map plane by its latitude and longitude.
  - Each node glows with an intensity proportional to its current value on the map.
  - The number of nodes always equals the number of slots in the auction.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - For an auction of 6 slots, :LondonMapScene: renders exactly 6 slot nodes.
  - Each node is placed at the projected position of its slot's latitude and longitude.

- Implement :BidEdge: animations driven by bids.
  - When a :Bid: occurs in a :RoundEvent:, a transient :BidEdge: is drawn from the bidding agent's marker to the slot.
  - Each :BidEdge: fades out shortly after it appears so the scene reflects only recent bidding activity.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - A round in which two distinct bids occur draws two :BidEdge: edges.
  - Each edge connects the correct agent marker to the correct slot node, and both fade out after the round.

- Implement :AuctionHUD: as the round ticker overlay.
  - It shows the current round number, the standing bid for each contested slot, and every agent's remaining budget.
  - It updates on each incoming :RoundEvent:.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - When a :RoundEvent: for round 3 arrives with two contested slots, the :AuctionHUD: shows round 3.
  - It also shows both slots' standing bids and all agents' remaining budgets.

- Implement :ClearingPulse: triggered by clearing results.
  - When the :ClearingResult: for a slot arrives, its node plays a settling pulse and locks to the winner's colour.
  - The node then shows the slot's final clearingPrice taken verbatim from the :ClearingResult:.
  - The displayed winner and price are never recomputed in the app.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - For scenario S1 cleared by arbiter-core, the slot node locks to agent A's colour and displays the price 140.
  - The displayed values match the :ClearingResult: exactly, with no recomputation in the app.

- Implement :ScorecardPanel: displaying each :AgentScorecard:.
  - For every agent it shows surplusCaptured, overpayment, leftOnTable, and the concessionErrors with their reasons.
  - Every money figure is taken verbatim from the :AgentScorecard:; the app performs no arithmetic on these numbers.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - For scenario S1, agent A's :ScorecardPanel: shows the exact core figures: overpayment 10, surplusCaptured 40.
  - The panel lists the overbid-while-uncontested concession error.

- Implement click-to-explain in :ScorecardPanel:.
  - Clicking any money figure on a scorecard reveals the exact :AuctionEvent: items it was computed from.
    - Those events come from the :ClearingResult: auditTrail and the :AuctionLog:.
  - The explanation lists those events only; it never derives a new number.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - For scenario S1, clicking agent A's overpayment of 10 reveals the audit-trail events behind it.
  - Those events show the drop-out at 130 and the raise to 140 that the overpayment was derived from.

- Extend :ArenaOrchestrator: so a caller can watch the auction round by round.
  - The run accepts an optional round listener.
  - After each completed round, the orchestrator emits a :RoundEvent: to the listener.
    - The :RoundEvent: carries the round number, the standing bid per contested slot, the drop-outs so far, and budgets.
  - The orchestrator still returns the same final bundle when the auction ends.
  - Running without a listener behaves exactly as before — the listener is optional and changes no auction outcome.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - A headless three-round deterministic auction run with a listener calls the listener three times, in round order.
  - Each emitted :RoundEvent: carries the standing bid for every still-contested slot.
  - The final bundle returned by the run is identical whether or not a listener was supplied.

- Harden the Claude-backed :AgentRuntime: for in-browser use, with a deterministic fallback.
  - It reads its API key from the environment variable `VITE_ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`.
  - It calls the Anthropic messages endpoint with model `claude-sonnet-4-6`.
    - The request sends the header `anthropic-dangerous-direct-browser-access` set to `true`.
    - That header lets the call run from a browser.
  - It falls back to a deterministic, valuation-driven decision when no API key is set or the API call fails.
  - When a key is set but the reply cannot be parsed, the agent holds for that slot, matching the Claude-backed runtime.
  - The deterministic fallback decides per contested slot:
    - if the agent is the current leader, hold;
    - else if a one-increment raise stays within the agent's valuation and budget, raise by one increment;
    - else drop out.
  - With no API key set, a full auction must complete entirely on the deterministic fallback, making no network call.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - With no `VITE_ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` present, a Claude-backed :AgentRuntime: returns only valid, non-over-budget
    :BidDecision: values from the deterministic fallback, and makes no network request.
  - A full headless auction of four such fallback agents over one slot terminates with the slot cleared and a valid
    :AuctionLog:.

- Wire the live auction into the app entry point so clicking start runs and shows a full auction.
  - When the user clicks the start control, the app loads inventory through :InventorySource: and shows the resulting
    :BillboardSlot: items as nodes on :LondonMapScene:.
  - It creates 4 :AdvertiserAgent: items, each with a budget and a private per-slot valuation.
    - Each agent is wrapped as a Claude-backed :AgentRuntime: with the deterministic fallback.
  - It runs :ArenaOrchestrator: with a round listener.
    - Each :RoundEvent: updates :AuctionHUD: and triggers :BidEdge: animations on :LondonMapScene:.
  - When the auction ends, it plays :ClearingPulse: on each slot and shows one :ScorecardPanel: per agent.
  - While an auction is running, the start control shows a running state and cannot launch a second auction.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - Starting the app with inventory and agents supplied by deterministic fallbacks loads the slots onto :LondonMapScene:
    and, when the run finishes, renders exactly one :ScorecardPanel: per agent populated from the final bundle.
  - The money figures shown on each :ScorecardPanel: equal the bundle's :AgentScorecard: values, with no recomputation.
